ybe it’s not necessary since it has a one-to-one mapping for the library. They want active classes in their own files, so perhaps removing AsmTest could be reasonable, as it's just a placeholder. I wonder if deleting it might disrupt the workflow. Also, I might need to examine the generated dynamic report to see if the new tests are included. It sounds like some issues could stem from assertions or lambda tracking as well.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Improving Resource Handling**\\n\\nI’m considering how to strengthen the resource naming by using a non-constant name and handling the missing class path in a separate statement or catch block. I wonder if the instrumentation might miss constant calls. I should also add a helper method that constructs strings, instead of using a direct try/catch within an AssertJ lambda. \\n\\nThere’s potential for the positive path to fail in Native Image if the ClassReader class resource isn’t found, though the negative path should execute regardless.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying Metadata Usage**\\n\\nI’m trying to figure out how repository metadata should apply to the native library. For the generated dynamic access report, it seems like the metadata directory used in the native-image run should be relevant. I wonder if ClassReader.class might be in a dependency jar and if resource patterns need to include `.class` specifically with `resources` metadata.\\n\\nMaybe Native Image can treat class files as resources, and I could include all ASM class resources in the test resources metadata. Adding test resources to `src/test/resources/META-INF/native-image/reachability-metadata.json` might be okay, even though the user mentions tests under `src/test/java`.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering class naming patterns**\\n\\nI'm thinking about the class name pattern, where some Gradle configurations include \\\"*Tests\\\" instead of \\\"*Test.\\\" I see that there's an existing AsmTest run. It might be due to the test class file being under the `asm.asm` package while the artifact path includes the same name. Maybe the dynamic-access coverage class file mapping expects a sanitized class file name with the full package, but that's not the case. Should I write ClassReaderTest in the default package instead? No.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Troubleshooting compilation issues**\\n\\nI'm trying to figure out why my project isn't compiling. It seems like the external Gradle is running, but locally it’s not working. I wonder if it has something to do with untracked files that are present in the filesystem. Maybe the `.gitignore` in `tests/src/asm/asm/3.1/` is set to ignore the source files. I need to check that out and see if it’s causing the problem.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_GxdHva4HMK3qv5NYGVIG4en1|fc_01ee4737486337400169f50a378ba48190b00320f454981db7", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/asm/asm/3.1/.gitignore"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 4012, "output": 2403, "cacheRead": 27648, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 34063, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777666576239, "responseId": "resp_01ee4737486337400169f50a10b0388190b6890cdd8e2ab6ee"}}
